  "name": "Morrison COU2 — VAD hemolysis credibility assessment (Accepted)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under ventricular assist device (VAD) conditions. COU2 evaluates whether the computational model can predict absolute hemolysis levels for a Class III VAD device at Model Risk Level 5. Full 13-factor assessment performed; all factors evaluated and credibility evidence compiled. Decision: Accepted based on structured factor review and Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/vad-hemolysis-mrl5",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/vad-hemolysis-cfd-accepted",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/cfd-centrifugal-pump-hemolysis",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-experimental-hemolysis",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/monte-carlo-uq-results"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "type": "ContextOfUse",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "deviceClass": "Class III"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-bench-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Hemolysis index bench validation against FDA pump experimental data"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/uq-monte-carlo-sweep",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification sweep across 5 flow-speed operating points"
    }
  ],
  "wasDerivedFrom": "https://doi.org/10.1115/1.4035672",
  "wasAttributedTo": "https://uofa.net/synth/org/morrison-assessment-team",
  "generatedAtTime": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
  "hash": "sha256:a3f1c2e4b7d09e56f812340abc9871de23456789abcdef0123456789abcdef01",
  "signature": "ed25519:9f8e7d6c5b4a3f2e1d0c9b8a7f6e5d4c3b2a1f0e9d8c7b6a5f4e3d2c1b0a9f8e",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software must be developed under a quality management system with documented version control, unit testing, and change management procedures consistent with MRL 5 requirements.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) is developed under ISO 9001-certified QMS. Full version control history, regression test suite covering 98% of solver modules, and formal change management logs were reviewed and found compliant with the required gradation level for MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Formal order-of-accuracy verification studies must demonstrate expected convergence rates for all governing equation discretizations relevant to hemolysis-driving flow features.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to Navier-Stokes and scalar transport equations. Observed second-order spatial convergence confirmed for velocity and shear stress fields. Temporal convergence verified at first-order for transient impeller passage simulations."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be computed for hemolysis index QoI using at least three systematically refined meshes; GCI must be below 5% for the primary hemolysis metric.",
      "rationale": "GCI study performed on three meshes (4.2M, 12.1M, 31.4M cells). GCI for hemolysis index at design point is 8.3%, exceeding the 5% threshold. Achieved gradation 3 rather than required gradation 4 due to unresolved near-wall refinement in volute tongue region."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented with uncertainty bounds and must cover the operating envelope specified in the COU.",
      "rationale": "FDA pump validation experiments conducted at 2500 RPM and 3500 RPM across flow rates 2.5–7.5 L/min. Temperature, hematocrit, and anticoagulant protocol documented per ASTM F1841. Uncertainty bounds on measured hemolysis index reported as ±12% (95% CI)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative metric of agreement (e.g., normalized RMS error or U95 validation uncertainty) must be computed and compared against acceptance threshold for hemolysis index predictions.",
      "rationale": "Normalized RMS error across all 5 operating points is 18.4% against experimental hemolysis index. Validation uncertainty U_val computed per ASME V&V 20 is 22.1%. These metrics place the output comparison at gradation 3; gradation 4 would require U_val below 10%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation activities must be directly traceable to the clinical endpoint of hemolysis and must include the hemolysis index as the primary scalar output.",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) computed from predicted shear stress histories along Lagrangian particle tracks. NIH is directly traceable to clinical plasma free hemoglobin thresholds. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, recirculation zone volume) are documented as supporting evidence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted on a geometry and at operating conditions sufficiently similar to the COU device and operating envelope to support extrapolation of credibility evidence.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is a surrogate for the proprietary VAD geometry. Geometric similarity index (blade angle, tip clearance ratio) is 0.74 relative to COU device. Operating condition overlap covers 60% of the COU flow-speed envelope. Gradation 3 reflects partial geometric and operational relevance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to solver residuals below 1e-5 for all equations; round-off error must be assessed and shown to be negligible relative to discretization error.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residuals below 5e-6 for continuity and momentum equations. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout; round-off error estimated at 1e-9, four orders of magnitude below GCI-estimated discretization error. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Evidence must demonstrate that analyst-introduced errors in model setup, boundary condition specification, and post-processing are controlled through independent review and documented simulation protocols.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent CFD analyst not involved in original model construction. Boundary condition specification checklist completed and archived. Post-processing scripts version-controlled and peer-reviewed. No use errors identified in independent review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence model and hemolysis damage accumulation model must be justified against available literature benchmarks and sensitivity studies must quantify model-form uncertainty contribution to hemolysis index predictions.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on published benchmark performance for rotating machinery flows. Power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen correlation) used; sensitivity study comparing Arora and Zhang correlations shows ±25% spread in predicted NIH. Model-form uncertainty is the dominant contributor to total prediction uncertainty, placing this factor at gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters (fluid properties, boundary conditions, geometric tolerances) must be characterized with uncertainty bounds and propagated through Monte Carlo analysis.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ performed with 1000 samples over 8 uncertain input parameters including blood viscosity (CV 8%), hematocrit (CV 5%), and impeller tip clearance (±0.05 mm). 95th percentile NIH prediction remains below clinical threshold. Input uncertainty contribution to total NIH uncertainty is 31%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental validation dataset must include sufficient replicate measurements to characterize inter-sample variability; minimum three independent experimental runs per operating point required at MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "FDA pump validation dataset includes two independent experimental runs per operating point rather than the required three. Inter-run variability in NIH is 9.4% (CV). Insufficient replication prevents full statistical characterization of experimental uncertainty, resulting in achieved gradation 2 against required gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A structured qualitative assessment of input parameter equivalency between validation experiments and COU operating conditions has been completed, covering fluid properties, rotational speed range, and geometric boundary conditions. Equivalency must be documented with traceability to COU specification.",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive qualitative assessment of input parameter equivalency was conducted by the credibility assessment team. Blood analog fluid properties (glycerol-water mixture, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s) used in validation experiments were evaluated against physiological blood properties expected in the VAD COU. Rotational speed range in validation (2500–3500 RPM) was reviewed against the COU operating envelope (2800–4200 RPM), with engineering judgment applied to assess whether extrapolation beyond the validated range is supportable. Geometric boundary conditions, including inlet cannula geometry and outlet pressure conditions, were compared qualitatively against the COU device configuration. The assessment team concluded that the input parameter space is sufficiently equivalent to support credibility transfer, based on the similarity of dimensionless flow parameters (Reynolds number range 1.2×10⁴–3.8×10⁴, specific speed Ns 1800–2400) and the conservative nature of the hemolysis model calibration. This qualitative determination is documented in the credibility assessment report and has been reviewed by the independent technical reviewer."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following review of all 13 credibility factors under the ASME V&V 40 framework, the credibility assessment team concludes that the CFD hemolysis prediction model meets the overall credibility threshold for the VAD COU at MRL 5. While several factors achieved levels below required levels (discretization error, output comparison, model form, test samples), the Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification demonstrates that the 95th percentile NIH prediction remains below the clinical hemolysis threshold with adequate margin. The qualitative input parameter equivalency assessment further supports credibility transfer from the validation dataset to the COU. Taken together, the structured factor evidence and supporting analyses provide sufficient confidence to accept the model for its intended use.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
